<TITLE> 3 RU teachers cleared of charges in one case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Rajshahi, Sept 9 (bdnews24.com)  A Rajshahi court Sunday cleared three teachers of Rajshahi University of charges pressed in a case filed under the emergency powers rules. They however would not be released from jail since another case is pending against them. Former vice chancellor Prof Saidur Rahman Khan, convenor of the Progressive Teachers Community professor Abdus Sobhan and associate professor of management Moloy Kumar Bhowmik were present in the court of Rajshahi metropolitan magistrate Rabiul Islam. Court inspector Mahbubul Quddus Siddiqui said the court quashed the case as the allegations were not proved. Prof Khan and Prof Sobhan were arrested on August 23 and Moloy Kumar Bhowmik the next day following incidents of large-scale clashes and ransacking at Rajshahi University on August 22 in a sequel to the student protests at Dhaka University. Motihar Police Station sub-inspector Faruk Hossain field a case, accusing the three charges of violating the emergency powers rules. They were produced before the court on August 25 and remanded for 10 days in custody. Faruk filed another case in connection with the student protest and ransacking and investigation officer sub-inspector Nasiruddin pressed charges against them on Sept 1. Three associate professors of the department of mass communication and journalism Dulal Chandra Biswas, Selim Reza Newton and Abdullah Al Mamun also stand accused in the case. Police on September 1 submitted a charge sheet against 14 people including two teachers of the university in another case on charges of setting a DGFI vehicle on fire during the clashes on August 22. bdnews24.c
